tps://web.archive.org/web/20150813041329/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/jeremy-thorpe-mp-who-revived-liberal-party-fortunes-but-whose-career-was-ended-by-his--trial-for-attempted-murder-9904558.html\n |ref=harv\n |url-status=dead\n}}\n* {{cite magazine\n |last=Murray\n |first=Douglas\n |title=The damning, shocking, depressing life of Jeremy Thorpe\n |url=http://blogs.spectator.co.uk/culturehousedaily/2015/01/the-damning-shocking-depressing-life-of-jeremy-thorpe/\n |magazine=The Spectator\n |date=5 January 2015\n |archivedate= 6 August 2015\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150806015501/http://blogs.spectator.co.uk/culturehousedaily/2015/01/the-damning-shocking-depressing-life-of-jeremy-thorpe/\n |ref=harv\n |url-status=dead\n}}\n* {{cite news\n |last=Rosenbaum\n |first=Martin\n |title=Jeremy Thorpe: Was there an establishment cover-up?\n |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-30349535\n |work=BBC News\n |date=6 December 2014\n |accessdate=7 June 2015\n |archivedate= 25 September 2015\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150925120944/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-30349535\n |ref=harv\n |url-status=dead\n}}\n* {{cite web\n |last=Stratton\n |first=Allegra\n |title=Jeremy Thorpe: I remember the lot\n |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2008/jan/28/liberaldemocrats.uk\n |newspaper=The Guardian\n |date=28 January 2008\n |archivedate= 16 August 2015\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150816092627/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2008/jan/28/liberaldemocrats.uk\n |ref=harv\n |url-status=dead\n}}\n* {{cite web\n |last=Tail\n |first=Stephen\n |title=Former Liberal leader Jeremy Thorpe dies\n |url=http://www.libdemvoice.org/former-liberal-leader-jeremy-thorpe-dies-43644.html\n |publisher=Liberal Democrat Voice\n |date=4 December 2014\n |accessdate=3 July 2015\n |archivedate= 27 July 2015\n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150727130405/http://www.libdemvoice.org/former-liberal-leader-jeremy-thorpe-dies-43644.html\n |ref=harv\n |url-status=dead\n}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Hansard-contribs | mr-jeremy-thorpe | Jeremy Thorpe }}\n* [http://www.libdems.org.uk/jeremy-thorpe-tributes \"Former Liberal Party Leader Jeremy Thorpe dies at 85\". Liberal Democrats tribute page, 4 December 2014]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box | title=Member of Parliament<br />for [[North Devon (UK Parliament constituency)|North Devon]] | before=[[James Lindsay (Conservative politician)|James Lindsay]] | after=[[Antony Speller]] | years=[[1959 United Kingdom general election|1959]]\u2013[[1979 United Kingdom general election|1979]]}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{succession box|title=Treasurer of the [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]]|years=1966\u20131967|before=[[Andrew Murray (Scottish politician)|Andrew Murray]]|after=Len Smith}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{UKLiberalLeaders}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Thorpe, Jeremy}}\n[[Category:1929 births]]\n[[Category:2014 deaths]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Trinity College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Deaths from Parkinson's disease]]\n[[Category:English male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:English memoirists]]\n[[Category:English people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:International opponents of apartheid in South Africa]]\n[[Category:Leaders of the Liberal Party (UK)]]\n[[Category:LGBT members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:LGBT politicians from England]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:People acquitted of crimes]]\n[[Category:People educated at Eton College]]\n[[Category:People educated at Hazelwood School]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the Oxford Union]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1959\u20131964]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1964\u20131966]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1966\u20131970]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1970\u20131974]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1974]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1974\u20131979]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n", "name_user": "2.28.151.43", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jeremy_Thorpe"}
{"title_page": "Margaret Croft", "text_new": "[[File:Adriaan Hanneman - Portrait of Lucy Hay (ne Percy), Countess of Carlisle (1599 - 5 November 1660) - 31.54 - Minneapolis Institute of Arts.jpg|thumb|right|Croft told '''Lucy Hay, Countess of Carlisle''' scandal from The Hague]]\n'''Margaret Croft''' (died 1637), lady in waiting to [[Elizabeth Stuart, Queen of Bohemia]].<ref>Nadine Akkerman, ''The Correspondence of Elizabeth Stuart, Queen of Bohemia'' vol 1 (Oxford, 2015), pp. 568-70: Mary Anne Everett Green, ''Elizabeth Electress Palatine and Queen of Bohemia'' (London, 1909), pp. 245, 260, 352, 423, 426: Lisa Jardine, [https://www.ucl.ac.uk/ucl-press/browse-books/temptation-in-the-archives ''Temptation in the Archives'' (UCL: London, 2015)], pp. 1-17.</ref>\nMargaret, Margery, or Madge Croft was a daughter of [[Herbert Croft (died 1629)|Sir Herbert Croft]] of [[Croft Castle]] and Mary Bourne, daughter and heiress of Anthony Bourne of [[Holt Heath, Worcestershire|Holt Castle]]. Worcestershire.\n\nHer father converted to Catholicism and died either in 1622 or in 1629, at [[English College, Douai|Douai]]. Her brother [[Herbert Croft (bishop)|Herbert Croft]] also converted but returned to the Church of England and became [[Bishop of Hereford]]. Margaret Croft or her sister Mary replied to her father's Catholic pamphleteering, and he responded in print with, ''Reply to the Answer of his Daughter M. C. which she made to a Paper of his sent to her concerning the Rom. Church'' (1619).<ref>James Doelman, ''King James I and the Religious Culture of England'' (Cambridge, 2000), pp. 109-10, supplies \"Mary Croft\".</ref> Her sister Mary Croft (b. 1598) married Richard Tomkyns of [[Monnington on Wye|Monnington]], and a letter of her cousin [[Brilliana Harley]] records a rumour she was involved in drafting an anti-Parliamentarian pamphlet of 1642, ''The Declaration or Resolution of the County of Hereforde''.<ref>Rachel Adcock, Sara Read, Anna Ziomek, ''Flesh and Spirit: An anthology of seventeenth-century women's writing'' (Manchester, 2014), p. 130: Timothy Taylor Lewis, ''Letters of the Lady Brilliana Harley'' (Camden Society, London, 1854), pp. 182, 263.</ref> Lucy Croft married [[Dudley Carleton (diplomat)|Sir Dudley Carleton]], a diplomat at [[The Hague]]. Elizabeth Croft (d. 1622) married Sir Thomas Cave, and her portrait is shown at Croft Castle.<ref>Owen George Scudamore Croft, ''House of Croft of Croft Castle'' (Hereford, 1949), pp. 85, 88, 92-4.</ref>\n\n==Working for the Queen of Bohemia==\n[[File:Philipp Moritz Hanau Muenzenberg.jpg|thumb|left|Croft was said to be the mistress of '''Philipp Moritz, Count of Hanau-M\u00fcnzenberg''']]\nCroft became a maid of honour or lady in waiting to [[Elizabeth Stuart, Queen of Bohemia]] in 1623. She was often known as \"Mrs Crofts\".<ref>Mary Anne Everett Green, ''Elizabeth Electress Palatine and Queen of Bohemia'' (London, 1909), pp. 260, 352.</ref>\n\nIn 1625 Elizabeth wrote letters to [[John Erskine, Earl of Mar (1558\u20131634)|John, Earl of Mar]] and [[Marie Stewart, Countess of Mar|Marie, Countess of Mar]] about one of their sons, perhaps Henry or Alexander, who had asked her if he could marry Croft, after she noticed their relationship. Elizabeth recommended Croft as \"an honest discreet woman and doth carie herself very well\".<ref>Mary Anne Everett Green, ''Elizabeth Electress Palatine and Queen of Bohemia'' (London, 1909), p. 423: ''HMC Mar & Kellie'', vol. 1 (London, 1914), p. 179: ''HMC 4th Report'', p. 527.</ref> No marriage ensued, Mar wrote to the queen in May 1626 that he could not have Alexander (or his seven brethren) marry according to her wishes.<ref>''HMC Supplementary Treport Mar & Kellie'' (London, 1930), pp. 174-5, 240.</ref> Mar gave no particular reason in the letter, [[Lisa Jardine]] points to a disparity in status. Thereafter Croft became linked with members of the Dutch court, especially [[Constantijn Huygens]].<ref>Lisa Jardine, ''Temptation in the Archives'' (UCL: London, 2015), pp. 4-6, 102-118: A. Worp (ed.), ''De Briefwisseling van Constantijn Huygens'', Deel I, 1608-1634 (The Hague, 1911), nos. 364, 369, 463, 695, 823.</ref>\n\nCroft was probably the author of a humorous account of a tour of North Holland taken by Elizabeth and [[Amalia van Solms]] in the summer of 1625. The account, written in French, was said to have been taken from a letter written in cipher from a maid of honour to her cousin in England.<ref>The French text is printed in Martin Royalton-Kisch, ''Adriaen Van de Venne's Album: In the Department of Prints and Drawings in the British Museum'' (London, 1988), and with an English translation in Lisa Jardine, ''Temptation in the Archive'' (London, 2015), pp. 108-119.</ref> The narrative is very different from formal accounts of royal progresses, and [[Elizabeth Dudley, Countess of L\u00f6wenstein]], a daughter of [[John Dudley (1569-1645)|John Dudley]], features in several comic episodes.<ref>Lisa Jardine, ''Temptation in the Archives'' (UCL: London, 2015), pp. 6-15: Mary Anne Everett Green, ''Elizabeth Electress Palatine and Queen of Bohemia'' (London, 1909), pp. 245-247.</ref>\n\nCroft has been identified as the mistress of \"H\", [[Philipp Moritz, Count of Hanau-M\u00fcnzenberg]], described in [[Frederick V of the Palatinate|Frederick's]] letters.<ref>Nadine Akkerman, ''The Correspondence of Elizabeth Stuart Queen of Bohemia'', vol. 2 (Oxford, 2012), pp. 126-8, 142-3: Lisa Jardine, 'In Search of the \"Real\" Doroth\u00e9e van Dorp', ''De Zeventiende Eeuw'', 25 (2009), pp. 44-6.</ref>\n\n[[Charles I Louis, Elector Palatine]], Elizabeth's son, put in a good word for Croft's brother Herbert Croft with the [[William Laud|Archibishop of Canterbury]] at Oxford in August 1636.<ref>Nadine Akkerman, ''The Correspondence of Elizabeth Stuart Queen of Bohemia'', vol. 2 (Oxford, 2012), pp. 519-520.</ref>\n\n==Disgrace and Death==\nShe returned to England in 1637. She had offended Elizabeth, who wanted the exact reasons for her dismissal kept secret, partly because they would prejudice Croft's chances of getting a reward from [[Charles I of England|King Charles]] and partly to prevent their public airing, and told them to [[Richard Cave|Sir Richard Cave]], rather than put them in a letter.<ref>Nadine Akkerman, ''The Correspondence of Elizabeth Stuart Queen of Bohemia'', vol. 2 (Oxford, 2012), pp. 594, 643.</ref>\n\nCharles Louis wrote to Elizabeth, his mother, on 24 May 1637 from [[Whitehall Palace]], mentioning an old quarrel he had with Croft, that she had fallen out with his sister [[Elisabeth of the Palatinate]] and that recently she had told [[William Craven, 1st Earl of Craven (1608\u20131697)|Lord Craven]] he was rude to her. In a second letter of 12 June 1637 from [[Greenwich Palace]] he described how Croft in conversation with [[Lucy Hay, Countess of Carlisle|Lady Carlisle]] had \"well stitched\" most the characters of Elizabeth's court at [[The Hague]] with \"censure sharp enough\". He wanted her to stay in London where she could do less harm. There was already a troublesome rumour that another lady in waiting, Elizabeth Dudley, Countess of L\u00f6wenstein, had boxed his sister Elisabeth's ear in the [[Frederick Henry, Prince of Orange|Prince of Orange's]] garden.<ref>Mary Anne Everett Green, ''Elizabeth Electress Palatine and Queen of Bohemia'' (London, 1909), p. 352: George Bromley, ''A Collection of Original Royal Letters'' (London, 1787), pp. 85, 87-9: Nadine Akkerman, ''The Correspondence of Elizabeth Stuart Queen of Bohemia'', vol. 2 (Oxford, 2012), pp. 602-3, 605-6, suggests the censure was in verses.</ref>\n\nShe died in London in 1637 and was buried in [[Westminster Abbey]] on 14 December 1637. In her will she hoped the Queen of Bohemia would settle her debts at [[The Hague]] amounting to \u00a3100. In London she owed Mr Berry in Paternoster Row for white satin for a waistcoat and mohair for a gown.<ref>Joseph Lemuel Chester, ''Westminster Abbey Registers: Harleian Society'', vol. 10 (London, 1869), pp. 64, 132, citing 'Will of Margery Crofts', TNA PROB 11/177/290: Owen George Scudamore Croft, ''House of Croft of Croft Castle'' (Hereford, 1949), p. 92-3 quoting TNA PROB 11/177/290.</ref>\n\n==References==\n* [https://artuk.org/discover/artworks/elizabeth-croft-d-1622-lady-thomas-cave-131660 Portrait of Margaret Croft's sister, Elizabeth Croft, Lady Cave, at Croft Castle, National Trust]\n* [http://resources.huygens.knaw.nl/briefwisselingconstantijnhuygens/brieven?reset=1&zk_correspondentid=1266 Huygen's letters to Margaret Croft, Huygens ING]\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Croft, Margaret}}\n[[Category:1637 deaths]]\n[[Category:Women of the Stuart period]]\n[[Category:16th-century English people]]\n[[Category:17th-century English people]]\n[[Category:Burials at Westminster Abbey]]\n[[Category:British maids of honour]]\n[[Category:English courtiers]]\n[[Category:17th-century English women writers]]\n[[Category:People from Herefordshire]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Adriaan Hanneman - Portrait of Lucy Hay (ne Percy), Countess of Carlisle (1599 - 5 November 1660) - 31.54 - Minneapolis Institute of Arts.jpg|thumb|right|Croft told '''Lucy Hay, Countess of Carlisle''' scandal from The Hague]]\n'''Margaret Croft''' (died 1637), lady in waiting to [[Elizabeth Stuart, Queen of Bohemia]].<ref>Nadine Akkerman, ''The Correspondence of Elizabeth Stuart, Queen of Bohemia'' vol 1 (Oxford, 2015), pp. 568-70: Mary Anne Everett Green, ''Elizabeth Electress Palatine and Queen of Bohemia'' (London, 1909), pp. 245, 260, 352, 423, 426: Lisa Jardine, [https://www.ucl.ac.uk/ucl-press/browse-books/temptation-in-the-archives ''Temptation in the Archives'' (UCL: London, 2015)], pp. 1-17.</ref>\nMargaret, Margery, or Madge Croft was a daughter of [[Herbert Croft (died 1629)|Sir Herbert Croft]] of [[Croft Castle]] and Mary Bourne, daughter and heiress of Anthony Bourne of [[Holt Heath, Worcestershire|Holt Castle]]. Worcestershire.\n\nHer father converted to Catholicism and died either in 1622 or in 1629, at [[English College, Douai|Douai]]. Her brother [[Herbert Croft (bishop)|Herbert Croft]] also converted but returned to the Church of England and became [[Bishop of Hereford]]. Margaret Croft or her sister Mary replied to her father's Catholic pamphleteering, and he responded in print with, ''Reply to the Answer of his Daughter M. C. which she made to a Paper of his sent to her concerning the Rom. Church'' (1619).<ref>James Doelman, ''King James I and the Religious Culture of England'' (Cambridge, 2000), pp. 109-10, supplies \"Mary Croft\".</ref> Her sister Mary Croft (b. 1598) married Richard Tomkyns of [[Monnington on Wye|Monnington]], and a letter of her cousin [[Brilliana Harley]] records a rumour she was involved in drafting an anti-Parliamentarian pamphlet of 1642, ''The Declaration or Resolution of the County of Hereforde''.<ref>Rachel Adcock, Sara Read, Anna Ziomek, ''Flesh and Spirit: An anthology of seventeenth-century women's writing'' (Manchester, 2014), p. 130: Timothy Taylor Lewis, ''Letters of the Lady Brilliana Harley'' (Camden Society, London, 1854), pp. 182, 263.</ref> Lucy Croft married [[Dudley Carleton (diplomat)|Sir Dudley Carleton]], a diplomat at [[The Hague]]. Elizabeth Croft (d. 1622) married Sir Thomas Cave, and her portrait is shown at Croft Castle.<ref>Owen George Scudamore Croft, ''House of Croft of Croft Castle'' (Hereford, 1949), pp. 85, 88, 92-4.</ref>\n\n==Working for the Queen of Bohemia==\n[[File:Philipp Moritz Hanau Muenzenberg.jpg|thumb|left|Croft was said to be the mistress of '''Philipp Moritz, Count of Hanau-M\u00fcnzenberg''']]\nCroft became a maid of honour or lady in waiting to [[Elizabeth Stuart, Queen of Bohemia]] in 1623. She was often known as \"Mrs Crofts\".<ref>Mary Anne Everett Green, ''Elizabeth Electress Palatine and Queen of Bohemia'' (London, 1909), pp. 260, 352.</ref>\n\nIn 1625 Elizabeth wrote letters to [[John Erskine, Earl of Mar (1558\u20131634)|John, Earl of Mar]] and [[Marie Stewart, Countess of Mar|Marie, Countess of Mar]] about one of their sons, perhaps Henry or Alexander, who had asked her if he could marry Croft, after she noticed their relationship. Elizabeth recommended Croft as \"an honest discreet woman and doth carie herself very well\".<ref>Mary Anne Everett Green, ''Elizabeth Electress Palatine and Queen of Bohemia'' (London, 1909), p. 423: ''HMC Mar & Kellie'', vol. 1 (London, 1914), p. 179: ''HMC 4th Report'', p. 527.</ref> No marriage ensued, Mar wrote to the queen in May 1626 that he could not have Alexander (or his seven brethren) marry according to her wishes.<ref>''HMC Supplementary Treport Mar & Kellie'' (London, 1930), pp. 174-5, 240.</ref> Mar gave no particular reason in the letter, [[Lisa Jardine]] points to a disparity in status. Thereafter Croft became linked with members of the Dutch court, especially [[Constantijn Huygens]].<ref>Lisa Jardine, ''Temptation in the Archives'' (UCL: London, 2015), pp. 4-6, 102-118: A. Worp (ed.), ''De Briefwisseling van Constantijn Huygens'', Deel I, 1608-1634 (The Hague, 1911), nos. 364, 369, 463, 695, 823.</ref>\n\nCroft was probably the author of a humorous account of a tour of North Holland taken by Elizabeth and [[Amalia van Solms]] in the summer of 1625. The account, written in French, was said to have been taken from a letter written in cipher from a maid of honour to her cousin in England.<ref>The French text is printed in Martin Royalton-Kisch, ''Adriaen Van de Venne's Album: In the Department of Prints and Drawings in the British Museum'' (London, 1988), and with an English translation in Lisa Jardine, ''Temptation in the Archive'' (London, 2015), pp. 108-119.</ref> The narrative is very different from formal accounts of royal progresses, and [[Elizabeth Dudley, Countess of L\u00f6wenstein]], a daughter of [[John Dudley (1569-1645)|John Dudley]], features in several comic episodes.<ref>Lisa Jardine, ''Temptation in the Archives'' (UCL: London, 2015), pp. 6-15: Mary Anne Everett Green, ''Elizabeth Electress Palatine and Queen of Bohemia'' (London, 1909), pp. 245-247.</ref>\n\nCroft has been identified as the mistress of \"H\", [[Philipp Moritz, Count of Hanau-M\u00fcnzenberg]], described in [[Frederick V of the Palatinate|Frederick's]] letters.<ref>Nadine Akkerman, ''The Correspondence of Elizabeth Stuart Queen of Bohemia'', vol. 2 (Oxford, 2012), pp. 126-8, 142-3: Lisa Jardine, 'In Search of the \"Real\" Doroth\u00e9e van Dorp', ''De Zeventiende Eeuw'', 25 (2009), pp. 44-6.</ref>\n\n[[Charles I Louis, Elector Palatine]], Elizabeth's son, put in a good word for Croft's brother Herbert Croft with the [[William Laud|Archibishop of Canterbury]] at Oxford in August 1636.<ref>Nadine Akkerman, ''The Correspondence of Elizabeth Stuart Queen of Bohemia'', vol. 2 (Oxford, 2012), pp. 519-520.</ref>\n\n==Disgrace and Death==\nShe returned to England in 1637. She had offended Elizabeth, who wanted the exact reasons for her dismissal kept secret, partly because they would prejudice Croft's chances of getting a reward from [[Charles I of England|King Charles]] and partly to prevent their public airing, and told them to [[Richard Cave|Sir Richard Cave]], rather than put them in a letter.<ref>Nadine Akkerman, ''The Correspondence of Elizabeth Stuart Queen of Bohemia'', vol. 2 (Oxford, 2012), pp. 594, 643.</ref>\n\nCharles Louis wrote to Elizabeth, his mother, on 24 May 1637 from [[Whitehall Palace]], mentioning an old quarrel he had with Croft, that she had fallen out with his sister [[Elisabeth of the Palatinate]] and that recently she had told [[William Craven, 1st Earl of Craven (1608\u20131697)|Lord Craven]] he was rude to her. In a second letter of 12 June 1637 from [[Greenwich Palace]] he described how Croft in conversation with [[Lucy Hay, Countess of Carlisle|Lady Carlisle]] had \"well stitched\" most the characters of Elizabeth's court at [[The Hague]] with \"censure sharp enough\". He wanted her to stay in London where she could do less harm. There was already a troublesome rumour that another lady in waiting, Elizabeth Dudley, Countess of L\u00f6wenstein, had boxed his sister Elisabeth's ear in the [[Frederick Henry, Prince of Orange|Prince of Orange's]] garden.<ref>Mary Anne Everett Green, ''Elizabeth Electress Palatine and Queen of Bohemia'' (London, 1909), p. 352: George Bromley, ''A Collection of Original Royal Letters'' (London, 1787), pp. 85, 87-9: Nadine Akkerman, ''The Correspondence of Elizabeth Stuart Queen of Bohemia'', vol. 2 (Oxford, 2012), pp. 602-3, 605-6, suggests the censure was in verses.</ref>\n\nShe died in London in 1637 and was buried in [[Westminster Abbey]] on 14 December 1637. In her will she hoped the Queen of Bohemia would settle her debts at [[The Hague]] amounting to \u00a3100. In London she owed Mr Berry in Paternoster Row for white satin for a waistcoat and mohair for a gown.<ref>Joseph Lemuel Chester, ''Westminster Abbey Registers: Harleian Society'', vol. 10 (London, 1869), pp. 64, 132, citing 'Will of Margery Crofts', TNA PROB 11/177/290: Owen George Scudamore Croft, ''House of Croft of Croft Castle'' (Hereford, 1949), p. 92-3 quoting TNA PROB 11/177/290.</ref>\n\n==References==\n* [https://artuk.org/discover/artworks/elizabeth-croft-d-1622-lady-thomas-cave-131660 Portrait of Margaret Croft's sister, Elizabeth Croft, Lady Cave, at Croft Castle, National Trust]\n* [http://resources.huygens.knaw.nl/briefwisselingconstantijnhuygens/brieven?reset=1&zk_correspondentid=1266 Huygen's letters to Margaret Croft, Huygens ING]\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Croft, Margaret}}\n[[Category:1637 deaths]]\n[[Category:Women of the Stuart period]]\n[[Category:16th-century English people]]\n[[Category:17th-century English people]]\n[[Category:Burials at Westminster Abbey]]\n[[Category:British maids of honour]]\n[[Category:English courtiers]]\n[[Category:17th-century English women writers]]\n[[Category:People from Herefordshire]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Margaret_Croft"}
{"title_page": "Bargebur", "text_new": "__FORCETOC__\n{{Infobox Ortsteil einer Gemeinde in Deutschland\n| name                   = Bargebur\n| Art                    = Stadtteil\n| Town                   = [[Norden, Lower Saxony|Norden]]\n| Wappen                 = \n| coordinates            = {{coord|53|35|45|N|07|13|44|E|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| Bundesland             = [[Lower Saxony]]\n| H\u00f6he                   =\n| Fl\u00e4che                 = 0.648\n| Einwohner              = 493\n| Stand= 2016-12-31\n| Postleitzahl           = 26506\n| Vorwahl                = 04931\n| Lageplan              = Norden-Bargebur.svg\n| Lageplanbeschreibung = Location of Bargebur within the borough of Norden\n}}\n\n'''Bargebur''' is an urban quarter in the east of the borough of [[Norden (East Frisia)|Norden]], northwestern Germany, and has a population of around 500 (as at 12/2016)<ref>[https://www.norden.de/index.phtml?mNavID=1.100&sNavID=549.20&La=1#5 Norden.de: Einwohnerzahl nach Ortsteilen]</ref>, who inhabit an area of just 0.65 km\u00b2.<ref>[https://www.norden.de/index.phtml?mNavID=1.100&sNavID=549.48&La=1 Norden.de: Ortsteile der Stadt Norden]</ref> The houses of Bargebur have been entirely absorbed within the built-up area of Norden.\nIn the south of the quarter, separated by the [[Bundesstra\u00dfe_72|B72]], which acts as a [[ring road]] around Norden here, is the ''Tidofelder Holz'', a forest in the neighbouring municipality of [[L\u00fctetsburg]]. Along the Fehn Canal runs the so-called ''Versch\u00f6nerungsweg''. On old maps  Bargebur is also called ''Bergum'' or ''Westekelbur''.\n\n== Geschichte ==\nNordern's townsfolk refused to allow the [[Reformed Church|reformed Christians]] to build their church within the then urban area. As a result, the Count of L\u00fctetsburg, [[Dodo II of Innhausen and Knyphausen]], allowed them to do so on his territory, which adjoined the municipal boundary. The town of Nordern made the construction of the church more difficult by making raids, which caused  material damage, until the reformed Christian, Grand Elector [[Frederick Willian of Brandenburg|Frederick William]] of [[Brandenburg]], who had occupied [[Greetsiel]] at this time, sent troops there in 1684, who protected the construction.\n\nOn 1 July 1972, Bargebur, which had belonged to the municipality of [[L\u00fctetsburg]] until then, was incorporated into the town of Norden.<ref>{{citation|editor-surname1=Statistisches Bundesamt|title=Historisches Gemeindeverzeichnis f\u00fcr die Bundesrepublik Deutschland. Namens-, Grenz- und Schl\u00fcsselnummern\u00e4nderungen bei Gemeinden, Kreisen und Regierungsbezirken vom 27. 5. 1970 bis 31. 12. 1982|publisher=[[W. Kohlhammer]]|publication-place=Stuttgart/Mainz|page=264|isbn=3-17-003263-1|date=   1983|language=German\n}}</ref>\n\n== Sights ==\n* Evangelical-Reformed [[Bargebur Church]]\n* Historic miller's house (meeting place)<ref>[http://www.norden.de/index.phtml?La=1&sNavID=549.48&object=tx%7C1652.521.1&sub=0 Stadt Norden: ''Bargebur'']; retrieved 30 January 2015</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{Norden (East Frisia)}}\n\n[[Category:Towns and villages in East Frisia]]\n[[Category:Geography of East Frisia]]\n[[Category:Aurich (district)]]\n[[Category:Geography of Lower Saxony]]\n", "text_old": "__FORCETOC__\n{{Infobox Ortsteil einer Gemeinde in Deutschland\n| Ortsteil               = Bargebur\n| Art            = Stadtteil\n| Town           = [[Norden, Lower Saxony|Norden]]\n| Ortswappen             = \n|coordinates       = {{coord|53|35|45|N|07|13|44|E|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n| Bundesland             = [[Lower Saxony]]\n| H\u00f6he                   =\n| H\u00f6he-Bezug             = DE-NN\n| Fl\u00e4che                 = 0.648\n| Einwohner              = 493\n| Stand= 2016-12-31\n| Eingemeindungsdatum    = 1972-07-01\n| Postleitzahl           = 26506\n| Vorwahl                = 04931\n| Lageplan              = Norden-Bargebur.svg\n| Lageplanbeschreibung = Location of Bargebur within the borough of Norden\n}}\n\n'''Bargebur''' is an urban quarter in the east of the borough of [[Norden (East Frisia)|Norden]], northwestern Germany, and has a population of around 500 (as at 12/2016)<ref>[https://www.norden.de/index.phtml?mNavID=1.100&sNavID=549.20&La=1#5 Norden.de: Einwohnerzahl nach Ortsteilen]</ref>, who inhabit an area of just 0.65 km\u00b2.<ref>[https://www.norden.de/index.phtml?mNavID=1.100&sNavID=549.48&La=1 Norden.de: Ortsteile der Stadt Norden]</ref> The houses of Bargebur have been entirely absorbed within the built-up area of Norden.\nIn the south of the quarter, separated by the [[Bundesstra\u00dfe_72|B72]], which acts as a [[ring road]] around Norden here, is the ''Tidofelder Holz'', a forest in the neighbouring municipality of [[L\u00fctetsburg]]. Along the Fehn Canal runs the so-called ''Versch\u00f6nerungsweg''. On old maps  Bargebur is also called ''Bergum'' or ''Westekelbur''.\n\n== Geschichte ==\nNordern's townsfolk refused to allow the [[Reformed Church|reformed Christians]] to build their church within the then urban area. As a result, the Count of L\u00fctetsburg, [[Dodo II of Innhausen and Knyphausen]], allowed them to do so on his territory, which adjoined the municipal boundary. The town of Nordern made the construction of the church more difficult by making raids, which caused  material damage, until the reformed Christian, Grand Elector [[Frederick Willian of Brandenburg|Frederick William]] of [[Brandenburg]], who had occupied [[Greetsiel]] at this time, sent troops there in 1684, who protected the construction.\n\nOn 1 July 1972, Bargebur, which had belonged to the municipality of [[L\u00fctetsburg]] until then, was incorporated into the town of Norden.<ref>{{citation|editor-surname1=Statistisches Bundesamt|title=Historisches Gemeindeverzeichnis f\u00fcr die Bundesrepublik Deutschland. Namens-, Grenz- und Schl\u00fcsselnummern\u00e4nderungen bei Gemeinden, Kreisen und Regierungsbezirken vom 27. 5. 1970 bis 31. 12. 1982|publisher=[[W. Kohlhammer]]|publication-place=Stuttgart/Mainz|page=264|isbn=3-17-003263-1|date=   1983|language=German\n}}</ref>\n\n== Sights ==\n* Evangelical-Reformed [[Bargebur Church]]\n* Historic miller's house (meeting place)<ref>[http://www.norden.de/index.phtml?La=1&sNavID=549.48&object=tx%7C1652.521.1&sub=0 Stadt Norden: ''Bargebur'']; retrieved 30 January 2015</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{Norden (East Frisia)}}\n\n[[Category:Towns and villages in East Frisia]]\n[[Category:Geography of East Frisia]]\n[[Category:Aurich (district)]]\n[[Category:Geography of Lower Saxony]]\n", "name_user": "Markussep", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bargebur"}
{"title_page": "French ship Roi-de-Rome (1816)", "text_new": "{{Other ships|French ship Sans Pareil|French ship Inflexible}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=Commerce de Marseille-IMG 5773.jpg\n|Ship caption=1/48 scale model of the ''Oc\u00e9an'' class 120-gun ship of the line [[:en:French ship Commerce de Marseille (1788)|''Commerce de Marseille'']], sister-ship of the ''Roi-de-Rome''. On display at Marseille naval museum.\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country=France\n|Ship flag=[[Image:Civil and Naval Ensign of France.svg|45px|French Navy Ensign]]\n|Ship name=''Roi de Rome''\n|Ship namesake=\n|Ship owner=\n|Ship operator=\n|Ship registry=\n|Ship route=\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship awarded=\n|Ship builder=\n|Ship original cost=\n|Ship yard number=\n|Ship way number=\n|Ship laid down=\n|Ship launched=\n|Ship sponsor=\n|Ship christened=\n|Ship completed=\n|Ship acquired=\n|Ship commissioned=\n|Ship recommissioned=\n|Ship decommissioned=\n|Ship maiden voyage=\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship out of service=\n|Ship renamed=\n|Ship reclassified=\n|Ship refit=\n|Ship struck=\n|Ship reinstated=\n|Ship homeport=\n|Ship identification=\n|Ship motto=\n|Ship nickname=\n|Ship honours=\n|Ship honors=\n|Ship captured=\n|Ship fate=\n|Ship status=\n|Ship notes=\n|Ship badge=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship class=[[Oc\u00e9an class ship of the line|''Oc\u00e9an'' class ship of the line]]\n|Ship type=\n|Ship tonnage=\n|Ship displacement=2&nbsp;700 [[tonne]]s\n|Ship tons burthen=\n|Ship length={{convert|65.18|m|abbr=on}} (196,6 French feet)\n|Ship beam={{convert|16.24|m|abbr=on}} (50 French feet)\n|Ship height=\n|Ship draught={{convert|8.12|m|abbr=on}} (25 French feet)\n|Ship draft=\n|Ship depth=\n|Ship hold depth=\n|Ship decks=\n|Ship deck clearance=\n|Ship ramps=\n|Ship ice class=\n|Ship power=\n|Ship propulsion=sail, 3 265 m\u00b2\n|Ship sail plan=\n|Ship speed=\n|Ship range=\n|Ship endurance=\n|Ship test depth=\n|Ship boats=\n|Ship capacity=\n|Ship troops=\n|Ship complement=1&nbsp;079 men\n|Ship crew=\n|Ship time to activate=\n|Ship sensors=\n|Ship EW=\n|Ship armament=*Rated as 120-gun:\n*lower deck: 32 [[36-pounder long gun|36-pounder guns]]\n*middle deck: 34 [[24-pounder long gun|24-pounder guns]]\n*upper deck: 34 [[18-pounder long gun|18-pounder guns]]\n*[[forecastle]]: 18 [[8-pounder long gun|8-pounder guns]], 6 36-pounder [[carronade]]s\n|Ship armour=Timber\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\nThe '''''Roi de Rome''''' (\"King of Rome\") was a [[first-rate]] 118-gun [[ship of the line]] of the [[French Navy]], of the [[Oc\u00e9an type 118-gun ship of the line|''Oc\u00e9an'' type]], designed by [[Jacques-No\u00ebl San\u00e9]].\n\nOrdered as ''Sans Pareil'', she was renamed successively ''Roi de Rome'', ''Inflexible'' and back to the ''Roi de Rome'' in 1812 alone.\n\nShe remained in an unfinished state until 1816, when her wood was found to have rotten, and she was broken up. The sound timbers were used for the refitting of [[French ship Wagram (1810)|''Wagram'']].\n\nA model of a 80-gun two-decker named ''Roi de Rome'' is on display at the [[Mus\u00e9e des Arts et M\u00e9tiers]] in Paris; the ship is fictitious and bears no connection to 120-gun ''Roi de Rome''.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Decenci\u00e8re |first1=Patrice |title=Les collections maritimes du Mus\u00e9e des arts et m\u00e9tiers |journal=Neptunia |date=June 2011 |issue=262 |page=37}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n; Notes\n{{Reflist}}\n\n; Bibliography\n*{{Cite book|first=Jean-Michel |last=Roche |year=2005 |chapter= |title=Dictionnaire des b\u00e2timents de la flotte de guerre fran\u00e7aise de Colbert \u00e0 nos jours 1 1671 - 1870 |isbn=978-2-9525917-0-6 |oclc=165892922 |page=}}{{Page needed|page number or exact name of the entry in the dictionary|date=September 2010}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Roi De Rome}}\n[[Category:Ships of the line of the French Navy]]\n[[Category:Oc\u00e9an-class ships of the line]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other ships|French ship Sans Pareil|French ship Inflexible}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=Commerce de Marseille-IMG 5773.jpg\n|Ship caption=1/48 scale model of the ''Oc\u00e9an'' class 120-gun ship of the line [[:en:French ship Commerce de Marseille (1788)|''Commerce de Marseille'']], sister-ship of the ''Roi-de-Rome''. On display at Marseille naval museum.\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country=France\n|Ship flag=[[Image:Civil and Naval Ensign of France.svg|45px|French Navy Ensign]]\n|Ship name=''Roi de Rome''\n|Ship namesake=\n|Ship owner=\n|Ship operator=\n|Ship registry=\n|Ship route=\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship awarded=\n|Ship builder=\n|Ship original cost=\n|Ship yard number=\n|Ship way number=\n|Ship laid down=\n|Ship launched=\n|Ship sponsor=\n|Ship christened=\n|Ship completed=\n|Ship acquired=\n|Ship commissioned=\n|Ship recommissioned=\n|Ship decommissioned=\n|Ship maiden voyage=\n|Ship in service=\n|Ship out of service=\n|Ship renamed=\n|Ship reclassified=\n|Ship refit=\n|Ship struck=\n|Ship reinstated=\n|Ship homeport=\n|Ship identification=\n|Ship motto=\n|Ship nickname=\n|Ship honours=\n|Ship honors=\n|Ship captured=\n|Ship fate=\n|Ship status=\n|Ship notes=\n|Ship badge=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=\n|Ship class=[[Oc\u00e9an class ship of the line|''Oc\u00e9an'' class ship of the line]]\n|Ship type=\n|Ship tonnage=\n|Ship displacement=2&nbsp;700 [[tonne]]s\n|Ship tons burthen=\n|Ship length={{convert|65.18|m|abbr=on}} (196,6 French feet)\n|Ship beam={{convert|16.24|m|abbr=on}} (50 French feet)\n|Ship height=\n|Ship draught={{convert|8.12|m|abbr=on}} (25 French feet)\n|Ship draft=\n|Ship depth=\n|Ship hold depth=\n|Ship decks=\n|Ship deck clearance=\n|Ship ramps=\n|Ship ice class=\n|Ship power=\n|Ship propulsion=sail, 3 265 m\u00b2\n|Ship sail plan=\n|Ship speed=\n|Ship range=\n|Ship endurance=\n|Ship test depth=\n|Ship boats=\n|Ship capacity=\n|Ship troops=\n|Ship complement=1&nbsp;079 men\n|Ship crew=\n|Ship time to activate=\n|Ship sensors=\n|Ship EW=\n|Ship armament=*Rated as 120-gun:\n*lower deck: 32 [[36-pounder long gun|36-pounder guns]]\n*middle deck: 34 [[24-pounder long gun|24-pounder guns]]\n*upper deck: 34 [[18-pounder long gun|18-pounder guns]]\n*[[forecastle]]: 18 [[8-pounder long gun|8-pounder guns]], 6 36-pounder [[carronade]]s\n|Ship armour=Timber\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\nThe '''''Roi de Rome''''' (\"King of Rome\") was a [[first-rate]] 118-gun [[ship of the line]] of the [[French Navy]], of the [[Oc\u00e9an type 118-gun ship of the line|''Oc\u00e9an'' type]], designed by [[Jacques-No\u00ebl San\u00e9]].\n\nOrdered as ''Sans Pareil'', she was renamed successively ''Roi de Rome'', ''Inflexible'' and back to ''Roi de Rome'' in 1812 alone.\n\nShe remained in an unfinished state until 1816, when her wood was found to have rotten, and she was broken up. The sound timbers were used for the refitting of [[French ship Wagram (1810)|''Wagram'']].\n\nA model of a 80-gun two-decker named ''Roi de Rome'' is on display at the [[Mus\u00e9e des Arts et M\u00e9tiers]] in Paris; the ship is fictitious and bears no connection to 120-gun ''Roi de Rome''.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Decenci\u00e8re |first1=Patrice |title=Les collections maritimes du Mus\u00e9e des arts et m\u00e9tiers |journal=Neptunia |date=June 2011 |issue=262 |page=37}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n; Notes\n{{Reflist}}\n\n; Bibliography\n*{{Cite book|first=Jean-Michel |last=Roche |year=2005 |chapter= |title=Dictionnaire des b\u00e2timents de la flotte de guerre fran\u00e7aise de Colbert \u00e0 nos jours 1 1671 - 1870 |isbn=978-2-9525917-0-6 |oclc=165892922 |page=}}{{Page needed|page number or exact name of the entry in the dictionary|date=September 2010}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Roi De Rome}}\n[[Category:Ships of the line of the French Navy]]\n[[Category:Oc\u00e9an-class ships of the line]]\n", "name_user": "Rama", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/French_ship_Roi-de-Rome_(1816)"}
{"title_page": "Choe Su-hon", "text_new": "{{Korean name|Choe}}\n{{Infobox Korean name\n|context=north\n|hangul=\ucd5c\uc218\ud5cc\n|hanja={{linktext|\u5d14|\u5b88|\u61b2|}}\n|rr=Choe Su-heon\n|mr=Ch'oe Suh\u014fn\n|text=<ref name=nkinfo/>\n}}\n\n'''Choe Su-hon''' ({{lang|ko|\ucd5c\uc218\ud5cc}}, born 7 October 1939<ref name=nkinfo>{{Cite web |script-title=ko:\ucd5c\uc218\ud5cc(\ub0a8\uc131) |publisher=Ministry of Unification |work=nkinfo.unikorea.go.kr |access-date=26 April 2019 |url= http://nkinfo.unikorea.go.kr/nkp/theme/viewPeople.do?nkpmno=1226 |language=ko  }}</ref>) is the former vice [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (North Korea)|foreign minister]] of [[North Korea]]<ref>{{cite web|title=N Korea hits out at US sanctions|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/asia-pacific/5383452.stm|website=BBC NEWS - World - Asia-Pacific|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=18 December 2015|date=27 September 2006}}</ref> who dealt principally with [[North Korea\u2013European Union relations|North Korea's relations with the European Union]]. He was replaced in this role in 2005 by [[Kung Sok-ung]]. It is unclear what position Choe now holds.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*https://www.un.org/webcast/ga/61/pdfs/korea-e.pdf\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Choe, Su-hon}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of North Korea]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n\n{{NorthKorea-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Korean name|Choe}}\n{{Infobox Korean name\n|context=north\n|hangul=\ucd5c\uc218\ud5cc\n|hanja={{linktext|\u5d14|\u5b88|\u61b2|}}\n|rr=Choe Su-heon\n|mr=Ch'oe Suh\u014fn\n|text=<ref name=nkinfo/>\n}}\n\n'''Choe Su-hon''' ({{lang|ko|\ucd5c\uc218\ud5cc}}, born 7 October 1939<ref name=nkinfo>{{Cite web |script-title=ko:\ucd5c\uc218\ud5cc(\ub0a8\uc131) |publisher=Ministry of Unification |work=nkinfo.unikorea.go.kr |access-date=26 April 2019 |url= http://nkinfo.unikorea.go.kr/nkp/theme/viewPeople.do?nkpmno=1226 |language=ko  }}</ref>) is the former vice [[foreign minister]] of [[North Korea]]<ref>{{cite web|title=N Korea hits out at US sanctions|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/asia-pacific/5383452.stm|website=BBC NEWS - World - Asia-Pacific|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=18 December 2015|date=27 September 2006}}</ref> who dealt principally with [[North Korea\u2013European Union relations|North Korea's relations with the European Union]]. He was replaced in this role in 2005 by [[Kung Sok-ung]]. It is unclear what position Choe now holds.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*https://www.un.org/webcast/ga/61/pdfs/korea-e.pdf\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Choe, Su-hon}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:Government ministers of North Korea]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n\n{{NorthKorea-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Rakoon", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Choe_Su-hon"}
{"title_page": "Frankmusik", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=February 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name = Frankmusik\n| image = Frankmusik by idrewuk.jpg\n| caption = Frankmusik performing at [[Lovebox Festival]] in [[London]] on 18 July 2009\n| background = solo_singer\n| birth_name = Vincent James Turner\n| alias = {{hlist|Vincent Did It|Vincent Frank|Mr. Mouth {{small|(beat-boxing)}}}}\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1985|10|09|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Thornton Heath]], [[London]], England\n| genre = {{hlist|[[Synth-pop]]|[[dance-pop]]}}\n| occupation = {{hlist|Singer|songwriter|record producer|musician|remixer}}\n| instrument = {{hlist|Vocals|synthesizer|keyboards|beatbox}}\n| years_active = 2006\u2013present\n| label = {{hlist|Apparent|[[Island Records|Island]]|[[Cherrytree Records|Cherrytree]]|[[Interscope Records|Interscope]]|VDI USA Inc.}}\n| associated_acts = {{hlist|[[Louis La Roche]]|[[Natasha Bedingfield]]|[[Ashley Roberts]]|[[Colette Carr]]|[[Natalia Kills]]|[[RuPaul]]}}\n| website = {{URL|http://www.instagram.com/frankmusik}}\n}}\n'''Vincent James Turner''' (born 9 October 1985), better known by his [[stage name]] '''Frankmusik''', is an English [[synth-pop]] musician.<ref name=\"guardian07\">{{cite web |last=Lester |first=Paul |authorlink=Paul Lester |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2007/aug/23/popandrock2 |title=No 171: Frankmusik |work=[[The Guardian]]|date=23 August 2007 |accessdate=27 January 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nVincent was born on 9 October 1985 in the [[Thornton Heath]] district of the [[London Borough of Croydon]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Paphides |first=Peter |authorlink=Peter Paphides |url=http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/music/article6730569.ece |title=The world according to Frankmusik |work=[[The Times]] |publisher=[[News International|Times Newspapers]] |date=1 August 2009 |accessdate=14 August 2009}}</ref> He attended [[Christ's Hospital]] boarding school in West Sussex and was member of the house 'Maine A'. He entertained his housemates with constant piano playing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.answers.com/topic/frankmusik-1 |title=Frankmusik: Information from |publisher=Answers.com |accessdate=20 October 2011}}</ref> He completed a year-long [[Foundation Course|foundation course]] at [[Central Saint Martins College of Art and Design]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thelondonpaper.com/staying-in/music/hot-new-artist-alert-frankmusik |accessdate=12 August 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090808070255/http://www.thelondonpaper.com/staying-in/music/hot-new-artist-alert-frankmusik |archivedate=8 August 2009 }}</ref><ref>http://artslondonnews.co.uk/index.php?opt=article&siid=10307</ref> and went on to study at the [[London College of Fashion]], dropping out to concentrate on music.<ref name=\"guardian07\"/><ref name=\"click\">{{cite web | url = http://www.clickmusic.com/articles/8375/Interview-Frankmusik.html | title = Interview: Frankmusik | first = Becky | last = Reed | publisher = Click Music | accessdate = 27 January 2009 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090302185445/http://www.clickmusic.com/articles/8375/Interview-Frankmusik.html | archive-date = 2 March 2009 | url-status = dead }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===2007\u20132009: ''Frankisum'' EP and ''Complete Me''===\nDuring 2004, Vincent performed as a [[beatboxing|beatboxer]], under the name Mr Mouth.<ref>{{Cite news| url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/southampton/music/homelands_youthmusic.shtml | title = Teen DJs here we go... |publisher=BBC News  | date = 28 May 2004 | accessdate = 19 February 2009}}</ref>\n\nVincent released his debut EP, ''Frankisum'', in 2007. Former school friend and then assistant of A&R at [[Island Records]], Ben Scarr, introduced Island colleague Louis Bloom to Frankmusik's [[MySpace]] page, which was getting a significant number of hits at the time.<ref name=\"hitquarters.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.hitquarters.com/index.php3?page=intrview/opar/intrview_Bloom.html |title=Interview With Louis Bloom |publisher=[[HitQuarters]] |date=4 April 2011 |accessdate=18 April 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110704123311/http://www.hitquarters.com/index.php3?page=intrview%2Fopar%2Fintrview_Bloom.html |archive-date=4 July 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Although already known for high energy electro and happy hardcore, Frankmusik's signing to Island was in part because Bloom recognised a pop star performer beneath the electronic music, telling [[HitQuarters]]: \"Underneath all the madness there was some great hooks and melodies, and buried even deeper was a voice; it took a lot of time after signing for him to have the confidence to sing without putting loads of effects over his vocal.\"<ref name=\"hitquarters.com\"/>\n\nIn June 2008, Frankmusik remixed the second single by [[The Clik Clik]] ''Did You Wrong'', which appeared on the B-side of the 7\" single release.\n\nIn December 2008, Frankmusik made it on to the long-list of the [[BBC]]'s [[Sound of... (BBC poll)|Sound of 2009]] poll.<ref>{{Cite news| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7758169.stm | title = BBC Sound of 2009: The longlist | accessdate = 27 January 2009 | date=5 December 2008 |work=BBC News }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7766430.stm | title = BBC Sound of 2009: Frankmusik | accessdate = 27 January 2009 | date=5 December 2008 |work=BBC News }}</ref> In the UK, [[Gaydar Radio]] was the first national station to champion Frankmusik and tracks from his debut album, ''[[Complete Me]]''. Initially interviewed by Alex Baker as part of the station's coverage of National Student Pride, Frankmusik performed a number of live tracks, which were then playlisted as part of an album teaser.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.gaydarradio.com/UserPortal/Article/Detail.aspx?ID=23028 | title = Frankmusik Interview Transcript | date = 2 December 2008 | accessdate = 27 July 2009 | publisher=GaydarRadio}}</ref> His rise to fame was also followed closely by his local radio station, [[Radio Jackie|107.8 Radio Jackie]], which was the first station to broadcast his music.\n\nIn January and February 2009, he was the support act for [[Keane (band)|Keane]] on their [[Perfect Symmetry (tour)|Perfect Symmetry tour]] in the UK.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mixmag.net/content/frankmusik-support-erm-keane |title=Frankmusik to support, erm, Keane |date=8 January 2009 |accessdate=4 February 2009 |first=Nick |last=Stevenson |work=[[Mixmag]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090302174825/http://www.mixmag.net/content/frankmusik-support-erm-keane |archivedate=2 March 2009 }}</ref> In March 2009, he headlined National Student Pride in Brighton's seafront club Digital with Jodie Harsh and [[Dan Gillespie Sells]] ([[The Feeling]]). In June 2009, Frankmusik was support act for the [[Pet Shop Boys]] in London, Manchester and Liverpool. He did a short tour to launch the album ''Complete Me'', starting in Brighton on 17 July and taking in London, Glasgow and Manchester.\n\n''Complete Me'' debuted on the [[UK Albums Chart]] at number thirteen in August 2009,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://theofficialcharts.com/top40_albums.php |title=Official UK Albums Top 100 \u2013 22nd October 2011 |publisher=Official Charts |accessdate=20 October 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100301120330/http://www.theofficialcharts.com/top40_albums.php |archive-date=1 March 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> after its second single, \"[[Confusion Girl]]\", was A-listed by [[BBC Radio 1]]<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio1/playlist/ | title = Radio1 Playlist | date = 27 July 2009 | accessdate = 27 July 2009 |publisher=BBC }}</ref> and reached number twenty-seven on the [[UK Singles Chart]]. The other singles were \"[[Better Off as Two]]\", which peaked at number twenty-six, and \"3 Little Words\".\n\nIn August 2009, a more extensive UK tour was announced to take place during November and December 2009.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.frankmusik.com/news.php?item=105 | title = Frankmusik tour dates November and December 2009 | accessdate = 5 September 2009 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110711023516/http://www.frankmusik.com/news.php?item=105 | archive-date = 11 July 2011 | url-status = dead }}</ref> Just two days later on 20 August 2009, it was announced that Frankmusik would join the Perez Hilton Presents tour in Autumn 2009.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.frankmusik.com/news.php?item=106 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110711023526/http://www.frankmusik.com/news.php?item=106 | archivedate = 11 July 2011 | title = Frankmusik Joins 'Perez Hilton Presents' Tour This Autumn | accessdate = 5 September 2009}}</ref> Frankmusik was part of a line-up at [[The O2 Arena]] 3D ELEKTRO RAVE alongside [[Caspa]] and [[Rusko (musician)|Rusko]], [[Tinchy Stryder]], [[High Contrast]], and Dancing Robot Music.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.utrevents.com/event.php?eid=16846 |title=Under the Radar &#124; Event |publisher=Utrevents.com |accessdate=20 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nDuring recording and promotion of his debut album, Frankmusik remixed material by other artists, including [[Pet Shop Boys]]' \"[[Love etc.]]\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.7digital.com/artists/pet-shop-boys/love-etc-7/?src=alsoBy |title=Pet Shop Boys \u2013 Love etc. MP3 Downloads |publisher=7digital |date=15 March 2009 |accessdate=20 October 2011}}</ref> [[Lady Gaga]]'s \"[[Eh Eh (Nothing Else I Can Say)]]\",<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arjanwrites.com/arjanwrites/2009/03/listen-to-lady-gaga-eh-eh-frankmusik-cut-snare-edit-remix.html |title=:: arjanwrites music blog ::: Listen to Lady GaGa \"Eh Eh\" (Frankmusik Cut Snare Edit Remix) |publisher=Arjanwrites.com |accessdate=20 October 2011}}</ref> [[Alphabeat]]'s \"[[Fascination (Alphabeat song)|Fascination]]\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.7digital.com/artists/alphabeat/fascination-8/ |title=Alphabeat \u2013 Fascination MP3 Downloads |publisher=7digital |date=1 September 2008 |accessdate=20 October 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100310100053/http://www.7digital.com/artists/alphabeat/fascination-8/ |archive-date=10 March 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and \"[[10,000 Nights]]\",<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.7digital.com/artists/alphabeat/10-000-nights-6/ |title=Alphabeat \u2013 10,000 Nights MP3 Downloads |publisher=7digital |date=1 September 2008 |accessdate=20 October 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100302011126/http://www.7digital.com/artists/alphabeat/10-000-nights-6/ |archive-date=2 March 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> [[Mika (singer)|Mika]]'s \"[[Relax, Take It Easy]]\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.play.com/Music/MP3-Download-Track/4-/7163072/Relax-Take-It-Easy/Product.html?aid=7579323 |title=Buy MIKA \u2013 Relax, Take It Easy (Frank Musik Mix) online at Play.com and read reviews. Free delivery to UK and Europe! |publisher=Play.com |accessdate=20 October 2011}}</ref> and [[CSS (band)|CSS]]'s \"[[Move (CSS song)|Move]]\",<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.ada-newreleases.com/ada-newreleases/200811/?pg=76 | title = ADA New Releases \u2013 November 2008 | date = 4 November 2008 | accessdate = 7 April 2009 | publisher = ADA New Releases | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110707082156/http://www.ada-newreleases.com/ada-newreleases/200811/?pg=76 | archive-date = 7 July 2011 | url-status = dead }}</ref> and has covered \"[[Rehab (Amy Winehouse song)|Rehab]]\" by [[Amy Winehouse]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mossipblog.com/2009/03/24/frankmusik-rehab-amy-winehouse-cover/ |title=Domain Brokerage for Buyers |publisher=Mossipblog.com |accessdate=20 October 2011}}</ref> and [[The Postal Service]]'s \"[[Such Great Heights]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.last.fm/music/Frankmusik/_/Such+Great+Heights |title=Frankmusik \u2013 Such Great Heights \u2013 Listening & stats at |publisher=Last.fm |date=11 February 2009 |accessdate=20 October 2011}}</ref> Frankmusik also co-produced \"First Place\" on [[Tinchy Stryder]]'s 2009 album, ''[[Catch 22 (Tinchy Stryder album)|Catch 22]]'', and \"Wish I Stayed\" on [[Ellie Goulding]]'s ''[[Lights (Ellie Goulding album)|Lights]]'' (2010).\n\n===2010\u20132011: ''Do It in the AM''===\nIn 2010, he featured on a [[Far East Movement]] track called \"Fighting for Air\", from their album ''[[Free Wired]]''; he also appeared in Far East Movement's music video for \"[[Rocketeer (song)|Rocketeer]]\" with [[Colette Carr]] and [[Mohombi]]. The same year he collaborated with [[Computer Club (band)|Computer Club]] on a track called \"Losing Streak\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://dailybeatz.com/2010/05/16/computer-club-feat-frankmusik-losing-streak/ |title=Computer Club feat. Frankmusik \u2013 Losing Streak |publisher=dailybeatz |date=16 May 2010 |accessdate=20 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nIt was announced in February 2011 that he has begun work producing the new [[Erasure]] album in Maine.  Entitled ''[[Tomorrow's World (Erasure album)|Tomorrow's World]]'', this was released on 3 October 2011 in the UK, and 4 October 2011 in the USA. During October and November 2011 Frankmusik was the supporting act on the Erasure tour across the US and Europe.\n\nIn an April 2011 interview, his A&R Louis Bloom said that Frankmusik was at work on his upcoming album. According to Bloom: \"The challenge has been for him to simplify the structure of his songwriting whilst still encouraging him into taking risks on the production duties.\"<ref name=\"hitquarters.com\"/> The album, ''[[Do It in the AM]]'', was released in September 2011 and peaked at number 178 on the UK Albums Chart.\n\nOn 19 October 2011 Frankmusik announced via his official [[Twitter]] page that he had parted ways with his UK label, Island Records.<ref>{{cite web |last=Copsey |first=Robert |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a346401/frankmusik-dropped-by-record-label.html |title=Frankmusik dropped by record label |publisher=[[Digital Spy]] |date=19 October 2011 |accessdate=23 December 2011}}</ref>\n\n===2012\u20132013: ''Between''===\nIn an interview with music blog Flop of the Pops on 3 January 2012, Frankmusik announced that he would change his stage name to Vincent Did It, along with the exclusive premiere of a song titled \"Dynamo\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://flopofthepops.blogspot.com/2012/01/exclusive-premiere-vincent-did-it.html |title=EXCLUSIVE PREMIERE: Vincent Did It \u2013 Dynamo (Song & Q&A) |publisher=Flop of the Pops |date=3 January 2012 |accessdate=7 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Copsey |first=Robert |url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/music/news/a358578/frankmusik-drops-stage-name-announces-new-project.html |title=Frankmusik drops stage name, announces new project |publisher=[[Digital Spy]] |date=5 January 2012 |accessdate=10 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 March 2012 Turner announced on his Twitter page that he has decided once again to go by his former stage name, Frankmusik.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=frankmusik|author=Vincent Frank|number=178372590556037122|date=10 March 2012|title=Had a change of heart, Frankmusik is back!. Wahoo! Feeling much better about everything.}}</ref> He then released two new acoustic demos titled \"I'll Know\" and \"This Is Who I Am\" on his official [[SoundCloud]] account for Frankmusik.<ref>{{cite web |last=Eames |first=Tom |url=http://www.digitalspy.com/music/news/a371254/frankmusik-unveils-two-new-demos-online.html |title=Frankmusik unveils two new demos online |publisher=[[Digital Spy]] |date=15 March 2012 |accessdate=16 March 2012}}</ref> Throughout 2012 Turner released thirteen demos online.\n\nOn 31 October 2012 Turner released a single titled \"Fast as I Can\". The song was released independently through digital distribution company [[Tunecore]] for international release. The song was originally meant to be the lead single off of his then-titled album, ''You Are Here''. Turner announced a track listing for the album and set a release date for 2013. The album was soon later scrapped, Turner claiming that he wanted to start fresh and not with \"songs [he] wrote six months ago\". On 14 February Turner released his sixth EP, titled, ''Far From Over''. The EP consisted of four songs and was released for free through his website. The EP was not available for purchase, instead it was free but fans were asked to donate to [[JustGiving]] what they thought the EP was worth.\n\nShortly after the EP's release, Turner announced that his third studio album, ''[[Between (Frankmusik album)|Between]]'', would be released on 1 April 2013. In March 2013, Turner announced that the album would no longer be released in April, along with revealing the cover art. The album's lead single \"Chasing Shadows\" was released on 9 May 2013 along with its video. On 11 May 2013 Turner announced that ''Between'' would be released on 7 June 2013.\n\nOn 10 September 2013, Turner released a full acoustic album called ''[[Between (Frankmusik album)#Between Us|Between Us]]'' featuring 10 songs from ''Between'' as well as a new song called \"Hymn\" to coincide with ''Between''.\n\n===2013\u20132014: ''By Nicole''===\nOn 13 December 2013 Turner released a single, \"[[Ephemeral Summer]]\", on iTunes and its video two days later. In January 2014 Turner announced he was working on his new album, titled ''[[By Nicole (Frankmusik album)|By Nicole]]'', and announced its lead single, \"Dear Nicole\". \"Dear Nicole\" was released through Turner's YouTube account on 14 February 2014.\n\nIn February 2014 to coincide with the launch of Season six of ''[[RuPaul's Drag Race]]'', [[RuPaul]] released his sixth studio album, ''[[Born Naked]]'', including the track \"Fly Tonight\" featuring Frankmusik.\n\nOn 1 April 2014 the album's third overall single, \"[[These Streets (Frankmusik song)|These Streets]]\", was released accompanying its music video through Turner's YouTube account and was made available the following day on the iTunes store.\n\nTurner announced through his YouTube, Facebook and Twitter pages on 18 April that the album would be released on Monday, 28 April 2014.\n\n===2015: ''For You''===\nOn 9 March 2015 Turner confirmed the title for his fifth studio album via Twitter,<ref name=\"twitter.com\">{{cite tweet|user=frankmusik|author=Vincent Frank|number=574912005552873473|date=9 March 2015|title=I can confirm the title of my 5th studio album is \"Not Right Now\"}}</ref> ''Not Right Now''. The first single, \"This\", was released on 4 May 2015.\n\nFrankmusik provided guest vocals for RuPaul's 2015 album ''Realness'' on the song \"Die Tomorrow\".{{Citation needed|date=July 2015}} This makes the second consecutive appearance of Frankmusik on a RuPaul album.\n\nOn 13 August 2015 Turner announced a new album title \"[[For You (Frankmusik album)|For You]]\",<ref>{{cite web|title=For You Announcement|url=https://www.facebook.com/frankmusik/posts/10153463977507777}}</ref> along with the track listing and a release date for October 2015.\n\n===2016: ''Day Break''===\nIt will be an 8 track EP and it will be released on 21 July 2016 (Digital + Streaming). A limited run of 500 copies will be made and the first 100 will be numbered and signed by Frankmusik himself.\n\n===2017: ''SS17 & AW17''===\n\"SS17\" is a six track EP that was released 17 June 2017 digitally. \"AW17\" followed later in the fall of 2017.\n\n===2020: Work with Louis La Roche ===\n\nIn 2020, Frankmusic appeared on two tracks by [[Louis La Roche]] which appeared on the album ''Saturday Night Griever'': these were \"Always\" and the single \"Desire\". Frankmusic also released a solo single in the first quarter of 2020, entitled \"Do What\".\n\n==Artistry==\nFrankmusik cites [[Daft Punk]], [[Erasure]], [[Electric Light Orchestra]], [[Razorlight]], [[Hard-fi]], [[Pet Shop Boys]], [[Late Of The Pier]], [[Oasis (band)|Oasis]] and [[Killa Kela]] as influences.\n\n==In popular culture==\n*Frankmusik appeared naked in the British gay lifestyle magazine ''[[AXM]]'' in 2009.<ref>[http://www.metro.co.uk/showbiz/757786-frankmusik-posing-naked-isnt-easy ''Metro'' UK: Frankmusik \u2013 Posing naked isn't easy]</ref>\n*A lyrical reference is made to Frankmusik in the [[Colette Carr]] song \"[[(We Do It) Primo]]\". A drawing of Frankmusik and his Logo are also displayed on a screen behind Colette Carr when the reference is made. He also produced and co-wrote the track.<ref>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0YpcrgBDKxg ''VEVO'' Colette Carr \u2013 (We Do It) Primo]</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Album details\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"2\"| Peak chart positions\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:4em;font-size:90%;\"| [[UK Albums Chart|UK]]<br><ref name=uk>{{cite web|url=http://www.theofficialcharts.com/artist/_/frankmusik/|archive-url=https://archive.is/20130204114434/http://www.theofficialcharts.com/artist/_/frankmusik/|url-status=dead|archive-date=4 February 2013|title=UK Charts > Frankmusik|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]}}</ref>\n\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:4em;font-size:90%;\"| [[Irish Albums Chart|IRE]]<br/><ref name=ire>{{cite web|url=http://irish-charts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Frankmusik|title=Frankmusik \u2013 Irish Charts|publisher=irish-charts.com/ Hung Medien}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Complete Me]]''\n|\n* Released: 31 July 2009\n* Label: [[Island Records|Island]]\n| 13 || 88\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Do It in the AM]]''\n|\n* Released: 23 September 2011\n* Label: [[Island Records|Island]]\n| \u2014 || \u2014\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | '' Between''\n|\n* Released: 7 June 2013\n* Label: Self-released\n| \u2014 || \u2014\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | '' By Nicole''\n|\n* Released: 28 April 2014\n* Label: Self-releas