{"title_page": "Margaret Bullock (journalist)", "text_new": "'''Margaret Bullock''' (n\u00e9e''': Carson'''), also known as '''Tua-o-rangi''', (4 January 1845 [[Auckland, New Zealand]] &ndash;17 June 1903 [[Wanganui, New Zealand]]) was a New Zealand journalist, writer, [[feminist]] and [[social reformer]].\n\n== Biography ==\nAlthough there is little known about Margaret Bullock's early life, at age 24 she married George Bullock, a warehouse-man, on 10 February 1869 in Auckland.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=The Suffragists: Women Who Worked for the Vote|last=Labrum|first=Bronwyn|publisher=Bridget Williams Books|year=1993|isbn=0908912382|location=Wellington|pages=33\u201337|chapter=Bullock, Margaret}}</ref> After eight years of marriage and the birth of five children, Margaret Bullock became a widow when her husband George died at sea aboard the ''May Queen'' in 1877.<ref name=\":0\" /> She then moved her family down to [[Whanganui|Wanganui]] to work as a reporter for the ''[[Wanganui Chronicle]]'', owned by her brother, Gilbert Carson.<ref name=\":0\" /> As reporter and assistant editor for the [[Wanganui Chronicle]], Bullock became one of New Zealand's first female parliamentary reporters. Under her [[pseudonym]], Tua-o-rangi, Bullock published her first and only novel, ''Utu: a story of love, hate, and revenge''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nzetc.victoria.ac.nz/tm/scholarly/tei-TuaUtu.html|title=Utu: A Story of Love, Hate and Revenge {{!}} NZETC|website=nzetc.victoria.ac.nz|access-date=2019-10-02}}</ref> in 1894.\n\nIn 1902, Margaret Bullock was diagnosed with cancer and was forced to withdraw from political activism and retired from many of her suffrage organisations and committees. At the age of 57, Bullock died from cancer on 17 June 1903 at her home in Wanganui.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Labrum|first=Bronwyn|date=1990|title=For the better discharge of our duties|url=|journal=Women's Studies Journal|volume=6|pages=136\u2013152|via=}}</ref>\n\n== Political Activism ==\nIn 1893, Bullock founded the [[Wanganui Women's Franchise League]], which worked towards getting the vote for women. Bullock was the vice president of the organisation since its establishment, and eventually served as president from 1893 to 1897.<ref name=\":0\" /> Later, her familiarity with politics eased the passing of the [[Women's suffrage in New Zealand|1893 Electoral Bill]] which gave New Zealand women the vote.<ref name=\"DNZB Bullock\" /> She helped run the [[National Council of Women of New Zealand]], serving as vice president in 1900, and was significant in encouraging political participation in women and defending their rights.<ref name=\"DNZB Bullock\">{{DNZB|title=Margaret Bullock|first= Bronwyn|last= Labrum|id=2b49|accessdate=23 April 2017}}</ref> Unlike other prominent suffragists at the time, Bullock was not supportive of the [[Woman's Christian Temperance Union|Women's Christian Temperance Union]] (WCTU), but continued to fight for equal rights and equal pay within Wanganui.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://nzetc.victoria.ac.nz/tm/scholarly/tei-TuaUtu.html Link to Bullock's novel, ''UTU: A Story of Love, Hate, and Revenge'']\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bullock, Margaret}}\n[[Category:1845 births]]\n[[Category:1903 deaths]]\n[[Category:New Zealand feminists]]\n[[Category:New Zealand journalists]]\n[[Category:New Zealand women journalists]]\n[[Category:New Zealand suffragists]]\n[[Category:19th-century New Zealand people]]\n[[Category:People from Whanganui]]\n[[Category:19th-century women writers]]\n", "text_old": "'''Margaret Bullock''' (n\u00e9e''': Carson'''), also known as '''Tua-o-rangi''', (4 January 1845 [[Auckland, New Zealand]] &ndash;17 June 1903 [[Wanganui, New Zealand]]) was a New Zealand journalist, writer, [[feminist]] and [[social reformer]].\n\n== Biography ==\nAlthough there is little known about Margaret Bullock's early life, at age 24 she married George Bullock, a warehouse-man, on 10 February 1869 in Auckland.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|title=The Suffragists: Women Who Worked for the Vote|last=Labrum|first=Bronwyn|publisher=Bridget Williams Books|year=1993|isbn=0908912382|location=Wellington|pages=33-37|chapter=Bullock, Margaret}}</ref> After eight years of marriage and the birth of five children, Margaret Bullock became a widow when her husband George died at sea aboard the ''May Queen'' in 1877.<ref name=\":0\" /> She then moved her family down to [[Whanganui|Wanganui]] to work as a reporter for the ''[[Wanganui Chronicle]]'', owned by her brother, Gilbert Carson.<ref name=\":0\" /> As reporter and assistant editor for the [[Wanganui Chronicle]], Bullock became one of New Zealand's first female parliamentary reporters. Under her [[pseudonym]], Tua-o-rangi, Bullock published her first and only novel, ''Utu: a story of love, hate, and revenge''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nzetc.victoria.ac.nz/tm/scholarly/tei-TuaUtu.html|title=Utu: A Story of Love, Hate and Revenge {{!}} NZETC|website=nzetc.victoria.ac.nz|access-date=2019-10-02}}</ref> in 1894.\n\nIn 1902, Margaret Bullock was diagnosed with cancer and was forced to withdraw from political activism and retired from many of her suffrage organisations and committees. At the age of 57, Bullock died from cancer on 17 June 1903 at her home in Wanganui.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Labrum|first=Bronwyn|date=1990|title=For the better discharge of our duties|url=|journal=Women's Studies Journal|volume=6|pages=136-152|via=}}</ref>\n\n== Political Activism ==\nIn 1893, Bullock founded the [[Wanganui Women's Franchise League]], which worked towards getting the vote for women. Bullock was the vice president of the organisation since its establishment, and eventually served as president from 1893 to 1897.<ref name=\":0\" /> Later, her familiarity with politics eased the passing of the [[Women's suffrage in New Zealand|1893 Electoral Bill]] which gave New Zealand women the vote.<ref name=\"DNZB Bullock\" /> She helped run the [[National Council of Women of New Zealand]], serving as vice president in 1900, and was significant in encouraging political participation in women and defending their rights.<ref name=\"DNZB Bullock\">{{DNZB|title=Margaret Bullock|first= Bronwyn|last= Labrum|id=2b49|accessdate=23 April 2017}}</ref> Unlike other prominent suffragists at the time, Bullock was not supportive of the [[Woman's Christian Temperance Union|Women's Christian Temperance Union]] (WCTU), but continued to fight for equal rights and equal pay within Wanganui.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://nzetc.victoria.ac.nz/tm/scholarly/tei-TuaUtu.html Link to Bullock's novel, ''UTU: A Story of Love, Hate, and Revenge'']\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2017}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bullock, Margaret}}\n[[Category:1845 births]]\n[[Category:1903 deaths]]\n[[Category:New Zealand feminists]]\n[[Category:New Zealand journalists]]\n[[Category:New Zealand women journalists]]\n[[Category:New Zealand suffragists]]\n[[Category:19th-century New Zealand people]]\n[[Category:People from Whanganui]]\n[[Category:19th-century women writers]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Margaret_Bullock_(journalist)"}
{"title_page": "The Substitute (2015 film)", "text_new": "{{more footnotes|date=May 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Substitute\n| image          = \n| alt            = \n| caption        = \n| director       = Nathan Hughes-Berry\n| producer       = Madeleine Sims-Fewer & Eva Sigurdardottir\n| writer         = Madeleine Sims-Fewer\n| starring       = {{unbulleted list|[[David Bamber]]|Madeleine Sims-Fewer|Ben Kerfoot|Haruka Abe|Anna Hogarth }}\n| music          = Alex Harwood\n| cinematography = Charlie Goodger \n| editing        = \n| studio         = <!-- or: | production companies = -->\n| distributor    = <!-- or: | distributors = -->\n| released       = {{film date|2015|01|08|df=y|London Short Film Festival}}\n| runtime        = 22 minutes \n| country        = Canada/United Kingdom/Iceland\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n| gross          = <!--(please use condensed and rounded values, e.g. \"\u00a311.6 million\" not \"\u00a311,586,221\")-->\n}}\n\n'''''The Substitute''''' is a 2015 short film<ref name=\"British Film Council\">{{cite web|author=British Film Council |url=http://film.britishcouncil.org/the-substitute |title=British Film Council - The Substitute |publisher=British Film Council |date= |accessdate=2015-03-01}}</ref> written by Madeleine Sims-Fewer and directed by Nathan Hughes-Berry. The film is inspired by Sims-Fewer's experience of life at [[boarding school]] and was shot on location at [[St Angela's Ursuline School|St Angela's Ursuline Catholic School]] in East London.<ref name=\"Booruffle Films\">{{cite web|author=Nathan Hughes-Berry |url=http://www.booruffle.com/the-substitute/4584295746 |title=The Substitute Short Film |publisher=Booruffle Films |date= |accessdate=2015-05-02}}</ref>\n\nThe film made its UK premiere at London Short Film Festival<ref name=\"London Short Film Festival 2015\">{{cite web|author=LSFF |url=http://shortfilms.org.uk/events/2015-01-10-new-shorts-gothic |title=LSFF Gothic Section 2015 |publisher=LSFF |date= |accessdate=2015-01-01}}</ref> and has gone on to pick up nominations at [[Fantasporto]],<ref name=\"Fantasporto\">{{cite web|author=Mario Dorminsky |url=http://www.fantasporto.com/news/161 |title=Fantasy Shorts selected Fantasporto 2015 |publisher=Fantasporto |date= |accessdate=2015-02-22}}</ref> [[Imagine Film Festival|Imagine Amsterdam Fantastic Film Festival]] where it competed for the Silver Melies,<ref name=\"Imagine Film Festival\">{{cite web|author=Eye |url=http://www.imaginefilmfestival.nl/en |title=Official Selection |publisher=Imagine |date= |accessdate=2015-03-22}}</ref> [[:de:Filmfest Dresden|Dresden Filmfest]]<ref name=\"Dresden Filmfest\">{{cite web|author=Dresden Filmfest |url=http://www.blog.filmfestivallife.com/2015/04/01/filmfest-dresden-program/ |title=Filmfest Dresden Official Selection 2015 |publisher=filmfestivallife |date= |accessdate=2015-04-01}}</ref> where it competed for the Golden Horseman and [[Bucheon International Fantastic Film Festival]]. The film was chosen to screen at the [[Cannes Film Festival]] as part of [[Telefilm Canada|Telefilm Canada's]] Not Short on Talent programme.<ref name=\"Not Short on Talent at Cannes 2015\">{{cite web |author=Telefilm Canada |url=http://canada-cannes2015.ca/en/films/category/273 |title=Not Short on Talent at Cannes 2015 |publisher=Telefilm Canada |accessdate=2015-05-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150506174014/http://canada-cannes2015.ca/en/films/category/273 |archivedate=2015-05-06 }}</ref>\n\n== Synopsis ==\n\nA young teacher takes a job at an unusual private school where she soon discovers that the boys have a sinister power over the girls. As the boys behaviour becomes increasingly threatening she uncovers the source of the girls fear; an ominous locked door at the back of the classroom.\n\n==Awards==\n* Best Short Screenplay (Second Place) - Slamdance Screenplay Competition<ref>https://variety.com/2013/film/news/slamdance-screenplay-prize-won-by-butterfly-children-1200710968/</ref>\n* Best Screenplay - Canadian Film Fest<ref>https://www.canfilmfest.ca/festival2016/2016/4/2/saturday-april-2nd-1pm</ref>\n* Best Short Drama (Winner) - The Smalls Film Festival<ref>http://www.thesmalls.com/festival</ref>\n* Best Short Film/Screenplay/Director - Little Rock Fantastic Cinema{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n* Best Short Film - [[Nitehawk Cinema|Nitehawk Shorts Festival]]<ref>http://www.nitehawkcinema.com/series/nitehawk-shorts-festival/</ref>\n* Best Short Film - Waves of Horror Film Festival{{cn|date=April 2020}}\n* Best Supporting Actor - British Horror Film Festival<ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20130729055337/http://www.thefilmfestivalguild.com/#!bhff2015/c1tz6</ref>\n* Honorable Mention - Brno16 Film Festival<ref>http://kinoart.cz/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/Z%C3%A1v%C4%9Bre%C4%8Dn%C3%A1-tiskov%C3%A1-zpr%C3%A1va-k-56.-Brn%C4%9Bnsk%C3%A9-16-z-20.-10.-2015.pdf</ref>\n* Special Mention - Corto Helvetico Al Femminile<ref>http://www.festival-chf.ch/#!films/galleryPage</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|3296160}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Substitute, The (2015 film)}}\n[[Category:2015 films]]\n[[Category:2015 short films]]\n", "text_old": "{{more footnotes|date=May 2015}}\n<!--- Don't mess with this line! ---><!--- Write your article below this line --->\n\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Substitute\n| image          = \n| alt            = \n| caption        = Festival Poster\n| film name      = <!--(for non-English films: film's name in its native language)-->\n| director       =Nathan Hughes-Berry\n| producer       =Madeleine Sims-Fewer & Eva Sigurdardottir\n| writer         =Madeleine Sims-Fewer\n| screenplay     = \n| story          = \n| based on       = <!-- {{based on |[title of the original work] |[writer of the original work]}} -->\n| starring       = {{unbulleted list|[[David Bamber]]|Madeleine Sims-Fewer|Ben Kerfoot|Haruka Abe|Anna Hogarth }}\n| narrator       = <!-- or: | n